            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Overview</span>
              <h2>What Are Corporate Bonds?</h2>
            </div>
            <p>Corporate bonds are debt securities issued by private and public companies to raise capital for business expansion, acquisitions, working capital needs, or refinancing existing debt. When you buy a corporate bond, you are lending money to the company in exchange for periodic interest (coupon) payments and the return of your principal at maturity.</p>
            <p>In India, the corporate bond market has witnessed tremendous growth, with outstanding issuance exceeding ₹43 lakh crore as of 2026. Companies across sectors — from banking and NBFCs to infrastructure and manufacturing — regularly issue bonds to fund their operations. SEBI has taken significant steps to deepen the market by enabling electronic bidding platforms and reducing face value to ₹1 lakh for listed bonds.</p>
            <p>Corporate bonds typically offer 1%–3% higher returns compared to government securities of similar tenure, compensating investors for the additional credit risk. This premium makes them an attractive option for investors seeking higher fixed-income returns while maintaining a manageable risk profile through proper credit analysis.</p>
          </div>

