          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header">
              <span class="section-tag">Benefits</span>
              <h2>Why Invest in Corporate Bonds?</h2>
            </div>
            <ul class="feature-list">
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Higher Yields Than Government Bonds</strong>
                  <p>Corporate bonds offer a credit spread of 1%–3% over government securities, translating to significantly higher income over time. A ₹10 lakh investment in corporate bonds earning 8.5% instead of 7% generates ₹1.5 lakh more over 10 years.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Credit Rating Transparency</strong>
                  <p>All corporate bonds in India are rated by SEBI-registered agencies (CRISIL, ICRA, CARE, India Ratings). These ratings provide clear guidance on the creditworthiness of the issuer, helping you make informed investment decisions.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Regular Income Payments</strong>
                  <p>Most corporate bonds pay interest semi-annually or annually, providing a steady income stream. This makes them ideal for retirees, conservative investors, or anyone building a fixed-income ladder.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Diverse Sector Exposure</strong>
                  <p>Corporate bonds span multiple sectors — banking, infrastructure, manufacturing, FMCG, and technology. This allows you to diversify across industries while earning fixed returns.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Secondary Market Liquidity</strong>
                  <p>Listed corporate bonds can be traded on NSE and BSE, providing exit options before maturity. Highly rated bonds from large issuers typically enjoy good trading volumes and tight bid-ask spreads.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li>
                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i>
                <div>
                  <strong>Capital Gains Potential</strong>
                  <p>When interest rates decline, bond prices rise. Investors who buy corporate bonds at higher yields can benefit from capital appreciation in addition to regular coupon income if they sell in a falling rate environment.</p>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

