  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Corporate Bonds</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>What happens if a company defaults on its corporate bond?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>In case of default, bondholders are treated as creditors and have priority over equity shareholders in the liquidation process. Secured bonds have collateral backing, improving recovery chances. SEBI has established a framework for debenture trustees to protect bondholder interests. However, recovery can take time through NCLT proceedings. This is why investing in high-rated bonds (AAA/AA+) is strongly recommended.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>What is the difference between NCDs and corporate bonds?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Non-Convertible Debentures (NCDs) are a type of corporate bond that cannot be converted into equity shares. Technically, all NCDs are corporate bonds, but not all corporate bonds are NCDs. Companies also issue convertible debentures, which can be converted to equity at predetermined terms. For retail investors, NCDs are the most common form of corporate bond investment available through public issues and secondary markets.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>How are corporate bonds different from FDs?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>While both offer fixed returns, corporate bonds typically yield 1%–2% more than FDs. Bank FDs up to ₹5 lakh are insured by DICGC, whereas corporate bonds rely on the issuer's creditworthiness. Bonds are tradeable on exchanges providing liquidity, while FDs carry early withdrawal penalties. Corporate bonds also offer potential capital gains when interest rates fall, which FDs do not.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>Is TDS deducted on corporate bond interest?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Yes, TDS at 10% is deducted on corporate bond interest if the annual interest exceeds ₹5,000. For bonds held in demat form, the depository participant handles TDS. You can claim credit for TDS deducted while filing your income tax return. If your total income is below the taxable limit, you can submit Form 15G/15H to avoid TDS deduction.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">
            <span>What is yield-to-maturity (YTM) in corporate bonds?</span>
            <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">
              <p>Yield-to-maturity (YTM) is the total return you can expect if you hold the bond until maturity, accounting for coupon payments, the purchase price, face value, and time remaining. If you buy a bond at a discount (below face value), YTM will be higher than the coupon rate. If bought at a premium, YTM will be lower. YTM is the most accurate measure for comparing bond investments.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

